        "client_msg_id": "accd915f-e13c-47bb-9ae9-bdf563f7c691",
        "text": "If your task is to read from a remote server that is readable by the world, then `ssh` buys you nothing.  \"Read in bulk, write, repeat til done\".  I think `ssh` comes in when people want to \/ need to write across insecure open internet links from one (public or private) site to another.  I use it locally between machines and my NAS, and remotely to smallish slice on a backup host.  And in all these cases `ssh` is involved as this governs access,  Now, for running a CRAN mirror, possibly even in DMZ behind firewall (or whatever your setup is) none of this matters.  You are simply planning to create a local cache, or at least that is my guess.   (And I have forgotten if the popular and powerful backend daemon `rsyncd` requires `ssh`.  I do not immediately see why it would but that may be a case.)",
